\subsection{\href{https://beta.lmfdb.org/knowledge/show/mf.siegel}{Siegel modular form}}
\begin{definition}\label{mf.siegel}
\uses{cmf,group.sp2gr,group.sp2gr.subgroup.congn,mf.siegel.halfspace,mf.siegel.koecher.principle,paramodulargroup.sp2gr,repn.highest.weight,repn.irrep.gl}
Let $g\ge 2$ be an integer, let
$\rho\colon \GL(g,\mathbb{C})\to \GL(V)$ be a finite-dimensional complex representation, and let 
$\Gamma \leq \GSp(2g,\Q)$ be an arithmetic subgroup.  

A holomorphic map $f$ on the 
\hyperref[mf.siegel.halfspace]{Siegel upper half space $\mathcal{H}_g$} 
taking values in $V$ is called a \textbf{Siegel modular form} of weight $\rho$ on $\Gamma$ if 
\[
f((a\tau+b)(c\tau+d)^{-1})=\rho(c\tau+d)f(\tau)
\]  
for all $\begin{pmatrix} a&b\\c&d\end{pmatrix}\in \Gamma$ (with $a,b,c,d \in \mathrm{M}(g,\mathbb{Q})$) and all $\tau\in\mathcal{H}_g$.

The arithmetic subgroups of $\GSp(2g,\Q)$ that we focus on are the following ones:
<ul><li>
\hyperref[group.sp2gr]{integral symplectic group:  $\Sp(2g,\Z)$}
 </li><li>
\hyperref[group.sp2gr.subgroup.congn]{Congruence subgroups of $\Sp(2g,\Z)$}
 </li><li>
\hyperref[paramodulargroup.sp2gr]{paramodular group:  $\Gamma^{\mathrm{para}}(d)\subset \Sp(2g,\Q)$}
 </li>
</ul>
Note in the case of \hyperref[cmf]{(classical) modular forms}, a 
holomorphicity condition at all the cusps of $\Gamma$ is required in the definition.
Due to the so-called \hyperref[mf.siegel.koecher.principle]{Koecher principle} such a condition is superfluous for Siegel modular form of degree $g>1$.

For each fixed choice of $\rho$ and $\Gamma$, the set of modular forms of weight $\rho$ on $\Gamma$ is a finite-dimensional complex-vector space denoted by $M_{\rho}(\Gamma)$.
Moreover if the representation $\rho$ is the direct sum of two representations 
$\rho=\rho_1\oplus \rho_2$ then the space $M_{\rho}(\Gamma)$ is isomorphic to
$M_{\rho_1}(\Gamma)\oplus M_{\rho_2}(\Gamma)$ and we can restrict ourselves to 
\hyperref[repn.irrep.gl]{irreducible representations} of $\GL(g,\C)$.

If the \hyperref[repn.highest.weight]{highest weight} of the representation $\rho$ 
is $(k,\ldots,k)$ i.e. $\rho=\det^{\otimes k}$ (note that $V$ is one-dimensional in this case) then the previous functional equation takes the form 
\[
f((a\tau+b)(c\tau+d)^{-1})=\det(c\tau+d)^kf(\tau)
\]
and $f$ is called a \textbf{scalar-valued Siegel modular form}. The space of such forms is simply denoted by $M_k(\Gamma)$. When $\dim(V)>1$, we usually talk about 
\textbf{vector-valued Siegel modular forms}.
 

\end{definition}


